          Does Elon Musk control Tesla?In 2016, Elon Musk was the chief exe=
cutive officer,=C2=A0chairman of the board, chief product officer, co-found=
er[1] and largest shareholder of Tesla Inc. He was also the co-founder, cha=
irman and largest shareholder of SolarCity Corp. He decided that Tesla, whi=
ch makes electric cars, should acquire SolarCity, which installs home solar=
 panels. So he =E2=80=9Cpersistently=E2=80=9D[2] raised the idea with Tesla=
=E2=80=99s board, which ignored him the first few times but eventually agre=
ed that Tesla should buy SolarCity. Terms of a deal were negotiated, with M=
usk more or less recusing himself from the negotiations. Eventually an all-=
stock acquisition was announced=C2=A0and=C2=A0presented to Tesla=E2=80=99s =
and SolarCity=E2=80=99s shareholders; a majority of the independent (i.e., =
not Musk) shareholders approved the deal, and it closed in November 2016.Th=
ere is an obvious conflict of interest when the CEO of a big public company=
 wants that company to acquire another company that he owns, particularly w=
here the target was maybe not in the greatest financial shape. (=E2=80=9CBy=
 any measure, SolarCity was in the midst of a liquidity crisis=E2=80=9D at =
the time, said a judge. =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t think SolarCity was financ=
ially troubled,=E2=80=9D said Musk.) And so some Tesla shareholders are sui=
ng Musk in a court in Delaware (where Tesla, like most U.S. public companie=
s, is incorporated), arguing that Tesla should not have bought SolarCity,=
=C2=A0that it overpaid, and that Musk should pay it back.The rules here are=
 a little strange.[3] Oversimplifying quite a bit, the main rule is that, a=
s a matter of theoretical Delaware corporate law, the=C2=A0board of directo=
rs=C2=A0runs the company and can decide what to do. If the CEO comes to the=
 board and says =E2=80=9Chey let=E2=80=99s do a transaction that benefits m=
e personally,=E2=80=9D the board can just say no. Or it can say yes, but if=
 it says yes it is =E2=80=94=C2=A0again, oversimplifying quite a bit =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0generally assumed to be acting in the best interests of the compan=
y, not just doing the CEO a favor. The =E2=80=9Cbusiness judgment rule=E2=
=80=9D gives directors enormous discretion to make decisions for the compan=
y, as long as they do not themselves have a conflict of interest.In practic=
e then there are always tons of arguments about whether they are conflicted=
, etc., and whether the business judgment rule should apply, but the point =
here is that the board is generally the decision-maker about mergers under =
Delaware law. So if you are mad about a merger, you sue the directors, and =
then you try to establish that they did something wrong. And in fact the di=
sgruntled Tesla shareholders=C2=A0did sue the directors for violating their=
 fiduciary duties, and they (other than Musk) =E2=80=9Cagreed to settle las=
t year for a combined $60 million, paid by insurance,=E2=80=9D while denyin=
g wrongdoing.But the disgruntled Tesla shareholders here aren't really mad =
at the board, they=E2=80=99re mad at Musk. They are suing him, too, for bre=
ach of fiduciary duty. You might intuitively think =E2=80=9Cyou were the CE=
O, you did a conflicted merger, and it was bad=E2=80=9D would be a good bre=
ach-of-fiduciary-duty case, but it doesn=E2=80=99t quite work that way, in =
part because as a theoretical matter the CEO=C2=A0didn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0do th=
e merger, the board did.=C2=A0Instead, the shareholders are suing Musk for =
violating his fiduciary duty to them=C2=A0as a controlling shareholder. The=
 rule under Delaware law is that, if someone=C2=A0owns 51% of the stock (or=
 rather 51% of the voting power, as some companies have dual-class stocks),=
 they have fiduciary duties not to exploit the other shareholders. After al=
l, if you control the voting power of the stock, you can replace the board =
whenever you want, and you can make them do whatever you want. So the law g=
ives you a duty not to use that power unfairly.And then there is a certain =
amount of vagueness where if someone=C2=A0owns like 45% of the stock but ha=
s lots of other power over the company =E2=80=94=C2=A0if he =E2=80=9Cexerci=
ses control over the business affairs of the corporation=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=
 then he is considered a controlling shareholder and has fiduciary duties a=
nd can be sued for doing a merger that other shareholders don=E2=80=99t lik=
e. And there=E2=80=99s no particular precision about the number; maybe 40% =
is enough, depending on what other sorts of control he has. Maybe 22%.A rou=
gh, not quite accurate, but intuitive way to put it is that if Musk was jus=
t the CEO, chairman, co-founder and largest shareholder of Tesla and did a =
conflicted merger, you can't sue him for it because he worked for the board=
 of directors and the board did the merger, but if he=C2=A0was the CEO, cha=
irman, co-founder and controlling shareholder of Tesla and did a conflicted=
 merger, you=C2=A0can=C2=A0sue him for it, because then the board worked fo=
r him.At the time of the SolarCity deal, Elon Musk owned 22.1% of Tesla=E2=
=80=99s stock. (It=E2=80=99s 17.7% now.) And now he is testifying in a tria=
l in Delaware about whether he was the controlling shareholder of Tesla.  I=
 guess it=E2=80=99s going well, I dunno:Elon Musk was cool but combative as=
 he testified in a Delaware courtroom that Tesla Inc.=E2=80=99s more than $=
2 billion acquisition of SolarCity in 2016 wasn=E2=80=99t a bailout of the =
struggling solar provider.Musk said he =E2=80=9Cdefinitely=E2=80=9D did not=
 have any sway over the company=E2=80=99s board when it approved the SolarC=
ity deal. The Tesla chief executive officer also denied vowing to retaliate=
 against any director who voted against the acquisition and said he had no =
control over their compensation or board committee assignments. =E2=80=A6Mu=
sk, during questioning by his attorney, said Tesla=E2=80=99s now-Chairwoman=
 Robyn Denholm set the final price and deal terms for the SolarCity buyout.=
The Tesla board kept Musk updated on the basic progress of the deal, but he=
 otherwise recused himself, Musk testified. He scoffed at the idea that he =
controlled Tesla=E2=80=99s shareholders.=E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t think it=
=E2=80=99s possible to control=E2=80=9D big institutional investors like Fi=
delity and T. Rowe Price, he said.It=E2=80=99s worth saying that the distin=
ction here doesn=E2=80=99t make a ton of sense. There are some companies wh=
ere the CEO owns 51% of the voting power and can just do whatever he wants,=
 and there are other companies where the CEO owns 20% of the voting power, =
or less, and can just do whatever he wants. Tesla=E2=80=99s board is famous=
ly, ludicrously deferential to Musk. Musk=E2=80=99s brother=C2=A0is on the =
board. In 2018, after Musk did a little fun securities fraud on Twitter, th=
e U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission=C2=A0ordered Tesla to get a more =
independent board and supervise Musk better; as a result Tesla now has an i=
ndependent chairwoman, though I am not sure that much else has changed, and=
 Musk is obviously un-supervisable.  Also:At one point, the self-described =
=E2=80=9CTechnoking=E2=80=9D said he doesn=E2=80=99t want to be CEO of Tesl=
a but felt he had no choice. =E2=80=9CI tried hard not to be the CEO at Tes=
la, but I had to or it would die,=E2=80=9D he testified. =E2=80=9CI rather =
hate being a boss. I=E2=80=99m an engineer.=E2=80=9D Musk has been the CEO =
of the company since 2008.If you are trying to prove that you don=E2=80=99t=
 control Tesla's board, I=E2=80=99m not sure saying =E2=80=9CI had to be th=
e CEO or it would die=E2=80=9D is helpful? Like you could imagine this dial=
ogue:Musk: Let's buy SolarCity.Board: No that makes no sense.Musk: Okay I q=
uit.Board: Wait you can=E2=80=99t quit, the company will die.Musk: Okay let=
's buy SolarCity.Board: =E2=80=A6Musk: =E2=80=A6Board: Fine.If you=E2=80=99=
ve got a wealthy impulsive CEO who is also the only person who could possib=
ly lead the company, you have to let him do whatever he wants! Just as a ma=
tter of fiduciary responsibility to shareholders, I mean, the directors sho=
