<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Does Elon Musk control Tesla?</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In 201=
6, Elon Musk was the chief executive officer,=C2=A0chairman of the board, c=
hief product officer, co-founder[1] and largest shareholder of Tesla Inc. H=
e was also the co-founder, chairman and largest shareholder of SolarCity Co=
rp. He decided that Tesla, which makes electric cars, should acquire SolarC=
ity, which installs home solar panels. So he =E2=80=9Cpersistently=E2=80=9D=
[2] raised the idea with Tesla=E2=80=99s board, which ignored him the first=
 few times but eventually agreed that Tesla should buy SolarCity. Terms of =
a deal were negotiated, with Musk more or less recusing himself from the ne=
gotiations. Eventually an all-stock acquisition <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24438987.264928/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGVzbGEuY29tL=
2Jsb2cvdGVzbGEtYW5kLXNvbGFyY2l0eS1jb21iaW5l/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9e0e21=
cf" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">was an=
nounced</a>=C2=A0and=C2=A0presented to Tesla=E2=80=99s and SolarCity=E2=80=
=99s shareholders; a majority of the independent (i.e., not Musk) sharehold=
ers approved the deal, and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.c=
om/click/24438987.264928/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy90ZXNsYS1tb3=
RvcnMtY2xvc2VzLXNvbGFyY2l0eS1hY3F1aXNpdGlvbi0xNDc5NzQyNDI0/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cB7c02327c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;">it closed</a> in November 2016.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Th=
ere is an obvious conflict of interest when the CEO of a big public company=
 wants that company to acquire another company that he owns, particularly w=
here the target was maybe not in the greatest financial shape. (=E2=80=9CBy=
 any measure, SolarCity was in the midst of a liquidity crisis=E2=80=9D at =
the time, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24438987=
.264928/aHR0cHM6Ly9jb3VydHMuZGVsYXdhcmUuZ292L09waW5pb25zL0Rvd25sb2FkLmFzcHg=
_aWQ9MjcwODMw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb5861a4c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">said a judge</a>. =E2=80=9CI don=E2=
=80=99t think SolarCity was financially troubled,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24438987.264928/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3=
NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9lbG9uLW11c2stdGFrZXMtc3RhbmQtaW4tY291cnQtdG8tZGVmZW5kL=
XB1cmNoYXNlLW9mLXNvbGFyY2l0eS0xMTYyNjA5ODk1OD9tb2Q9aHBfbGlzdGFfcG9zMg/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cB3149b18f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;">said Musk</a>.) And so some Tesla shareholders are suin=
g Musk in a court in Delaware (where Tesla, like most U.S. public companies=
, is incorporated), arguing that Tesla should not have bought SolarCity,=C2=
=A0that it overpaid, and that Musk should pay it back.</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">The rules here are a little strange.[3] Oversimplifying quite a=
 bit, the main rule is that, as a matter of theoretical Delaware corporate =
law, the=C2=A0<em>board of directors=C2=A0</em>runs the company and can dec=
ide what to do. If the CEO comes to the board and says =E2=80=9Chey let=E2=
=80=99s do a transaction that benefits me personally,=E2=80=9D the board ca=
n just say no. Or it can say yes, but if it says yes it is =E2=80=94=C2=A0a=
gain, oversimplifying quite a bit =E2=80=94=C2=A0generally assumed to be ac=
ting in the best interests of the company, not just doing the CEO a favor. =
The =E2=80=9Cbusiness judgment rule=E2=80=9D gives directors enormous discr=
etion to make decisions for the company, as long as they do not themselves =
have a conflict of interest.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In practice th=
en there are always tons of arguments about whether they are conflicted, et=
c., and whether the business judgment rule should apply, but the point here=
 is that the board is generally the decision-maker about mergers under Dela=
ware law. So if you are mad about a merger, you sue the directors, and then=
 you try to establish that they did something wrong. And in fact the disgru=
ntled Tesla shareholders=C2=A0did sue the directors for violating their fid=
uciary duties, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/244=
38987.264928/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9lbG9uLW11c2stdGFrZXMtc3=
RhbmQtaW4tY291cnQtdG8tZGVmZW5kLXB1cmNoYXNlLW9mLXNvbGFyY2l0eS0xMTYyNjA5ODk1O=
D9tb2Q9aHBfbGlzdGFfcG9zMg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC3149b18f" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">and they (other than Mus=
k)</a> =E2=80=9Cagreed to settle last year for a combined $60 million, paid=
 by insurance,=E2=80=9D while denying wrongdoing.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">But the disgruntled Tesla shareholders here aren't really mad at the=
 board, they=E2=80=99re mad at Musk. They are suing him, too, for breach of=
 fiduciary duty. You might intuitively think =E2=80=9Cyou were the CEO, you=
 did a conflicted merger, and it was bad=E2=80=9D would be a good breach-of=
-fiduciary-duty case, but it doesn=E2=80=99t quite work that way, in part b=
ecause as a theoretical matter the CEO=C2=A0<em>didn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>do=
 the merger, the board did.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Instead, =
the shareholders are suing Musk for violating his fiduciary duty to them=C2=
=A0<em>as a controlling shareholder</em>. The rule under Delaware law is th=
at, if someone=C2=A0owns 51% of the stock (or rather 51% of the voting powe=
r, as some companies have dual-class stocks), they have fiduciary duties no=
t to exploit the other shareholders. After all, if you control the voting p=
ower of the stock, you can replace the board whenever you want, and you can=
 make them do whatever you want. So the law gives you a duty not to use tha=
t power unfairly.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then there is a certa=
in amount of vagueness where if someone=C2=A0owns like 45% of the stock but=
 has lots of other power over the company =E2=80=94=C2=A0<a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24438987.264928/aHR0cHM6Ly9sYXcuanVz=
dGlhLmNvbS9jYXNlcy9kZWxhd2FyZS9zdXByZW1lLWNvdXJ0LzE5OTQvMjcyLTE5OTMtMy5odG1=
s/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBec960770" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;">if he</a> =E2=80=9Cexercises control over the bu=
siness affairs of the corporation=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 then he is considered =
a controlling shareholder and has fiduciary duties and can be sued for doin=
g a merger that other shareholders don=E2=80=99t like. And there=E2=80=99s =
no particular precision about the number; maybe 40% is enough, depending on=
 what other sorts of control he has. Maybe 22%.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">A rough, not quite accurate, but intuitive way to put it is that if Mu=
sk was just the CEO, chairman, co-founder and largest shareholder of Tesla =
and did a conflicted merger, you can't sue him for it because he worked for=
 the board of directors and the board did the merger, but if he=C2=A0was th=
e CEO, chairman, co-founder and <em>controlling</em> shareholder of Tesla a=
nd did a conflicted merger, you=C2=A0<em>can=C2=A0</em>sue him for it, beca=
use then the board worked for him.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At the t=
ime of the SolarCity deal, Elon Musk owned 22.1% of Tesla=E2=80=99s stock. =
(It=E2=80=99s 17.7% now.) And now he is testifying in a trial in Delaware a=
bout whether he was the controlling shareholder of Tesla. <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24438987.264928/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmx=
vb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMTIvZWxvbi1tdXNrLXRlbGxzLWNvdX=
J0LXRlc2xhLXMtc29sYXJjaXR5LWRlYWwtd2Fzbi10LWEtYmFpbG91dA/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cB5c056cf5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;"> I guess it=E2=80=99s going well</a>, I dunno:</p><blockquote><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Elon Musk was cool but combative as he testified in =
a Delaware courtroom that Tesla Inc.=E2=80=99s more than $2 billion acquisi=
tion of SolarCity in 2016 wasn=E2=80=99t a bailout of the struggling solar =
provider.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Musk said he =E2=80=9Cdefinitely=
=E2=80=9D did not have any sway over the company=E2=80=99s board when it ap=
proved the SolarCity deal. The Tesla chief executive officer also denied vo=
wing to retaliate against any director who voted against the acquisition an=
d said he had no control over their compensation or board committee assignm=
ents. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Musk, during questioning by=
 his attorney, said Tesla=E2=80=99s now-Chairwoman Robyn Denholm set the fi=
nal price and deal terms for the SolarCity buyout.</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">The Tesla board kept Musk updated on the basic progress of the deal=
, but he otherwise recused himself, Musk testified. He scoffed at the idea =
that he controlled Tesla=E2=80=99s shareholders.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">=E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t think it=E2=80=99s possible to control=E2=80=
=9D big institutional investors like Fidelity and T. Rowe Price, he said.</=
p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s worth saying that =
the distinction here doesn=E2=80=99t make a ton of sense. There are some co=
mpanies where the CEO owns 51% of the voting power and can just do whatever=
 he wants, and there are other companies where the CEO owns 20% of the voti=
ng power, or less, and can just do whatever he wants. Tesla=E2=80=99s board=
 is famously, ludicrously deferential to Musk. Musk=E2=80=99s brother=C2=A0=
is on the board. In 2018, after Musk did a little fun securities fraud on T=
witter, the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission=C2=A0<a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24438987.264928/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxv=
b21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMTAtMDEvdGVzbGEtd2lsbC10cnktdG8=
tYmUtbW9yZS1ub3JtYWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBeed7ecb4" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">ordered<em> </em>Tesla to get=
 a more independent board</a> and supervise Musk better; as a result Tesla =
now has an independent chairwoman, though I am not sure that much else has =
changed, and Musk is obviously un-supervisable. <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24438987.264928/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnL=
mNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMTIvZWxvbi1tdXNrLXRlbGxzLWNvdXJ0LXRlc2xh=
LXMtc29sYXJjaXR5LWRlYWwtd2Fzbi10LWEtYmFpbG91dA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC5c0=
56cf5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Al=
so</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At one point, the self-=
described =E2=80=9CTechnoking=E2=80=9D said he doesn=E2=80=99t want to be C=
EO of Tesla but felt he had no choice. =E2=80=9CI tried hard not to be the =
CEO at Tesla, but I had to or it would die,=E2=80=9D he testified. =E2=80=
=9CI rather hate being a boss. I=E2=80=99m an engineer.=E2=80=9D Musk has b=
een the CEO of the company since 2008.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">If you are trying to prove that you don=E2=80=99t control Tesla's =
board, I=E2=80=99m not sure saying =E2=80=9CI had to be the CEO or it would=
 die=E2=80=9D is helpful? Like you could imagine this dialogue:</p><blockqu=
ote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Musk:</strong> Let's buy SolarCity=
.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Board:</strong> No that makes no =
sense.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Musk:</strong> Okay I quit.<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Board:</strong> Wait you can=E2=80=
=99t quit, the company will die.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Mu=
sk:</strong> Okay let's buy SolarCity.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><str=
ong>Board:</strong> =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Musk:=
</strong> =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Board:</strong>=
 Fine.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you=E2=80=99ve got a=
 wealthy impulsive CEO who is also the only person who could possibly lead =
the company, you have to let him do whatever he wants! Just as a matter of =
fiduciary responsibility to shareholders, I mean, the directors should pref=
er approving a terrible conflicted deal that they hate if the alternative i=
s disappointing Musk and possibly losing him.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">But the point I want to stress here is that this is a matter of being a =
charismatic founder-CEO,=C2=A0<em>not a controlling shareholder</em>. The f=
act that Musk owns=C2=A018% or 22% of Tesla=E2=80=99s stock is not what giv=
es him power over Tesla; what gives him power over Tesla is that he is the =
CEO and product architect and visionary and social media manager, and it wo=
uld die without him, or so he and the board and let's face it the sharehold=
ers think. This has nothing to do with his shareholder voting power or his =
ability or inability, as a matter of technical corporate governance, to rem=
ove directors who disagree with him. It has to do with his personality, and=
 his job as CEO, and the love that retail shareholders have for him, and th=
e general backdrop that boards of directors of public tech companies tend t=
o be very deferential to charismatic founder-CEOs regardless of how many sh=
ares they own.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is intuitively tr=
ue, so you get a trial about whether Musk controlled Tesla=E2=80=99s board,=
 but the law has not quite caught up with the intuitions, so the trial is t=
echnically about whether Musk was a controlling=C2=A0<em>shareholder</em>. =
It seems obvious to me that Elon Musk controls Tesla=E2=80=99s board, but s=
omewhat unlikely that he is the controlling shareholder.=C2=A0I=E2=80=99m n=
ot sure=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24438=
987.264928/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvY2FjYmIwYjMtOWUwYi00ZjUyLTgx=
ZTEtOWNhY2ZkM2UxNTIx/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8b2ad3bd" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">what to do with that</a>:</p>=
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The decision could have significan=
t implications as corporate law grapples with the implications of all-power=
ful founder chief executives, particularly in the tech sector.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe case has the potential to provide more gu=
idance not only to courts, but also to deal planners, as to the factors cou=
rts are likely to take into account when determining whether someone is a c=
ontroller,=E2=80=9D said Ann Lipton, law professor at Tulane University in =
New Orleans.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway=C2=A0Musk =
also testified about <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
